  <!-- KEY TAKEAWAYS                     -->
  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="takeaways">
    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
    <div class="section-rule" style="background:var(--blue);margin-bottom:4px"></div>
    <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:0.9rem;margin-top:8px">What every trainer should walk away knowing from Chapter 9.</p>
    <div class="takeaways-grid">
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">1</div>
        <div class="ta-text">The skeleton is a living, adaptable tissue. Wolff's Law: exercise builds bone. Inactivity loses it. Resistance training is the most direct intervention for bone density.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">2</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Joints follow a mobility-stability alternating pattern. Dysfunction at one joint forces compensations above and below — leading to injury at neighboring joints.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">3</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Early strength gains come from neural adaptation (motor learning), not hypertrophy. Weeks 1–8 of a new program are dominated by the nervous system becoming more efficient.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">4</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Type IIa fibers are adaptable — training can shift their profile toward either endurance or power. Program accordingly for the specific demands of each client's sport or goal.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">5</div>
        <div class="ta-text">The 5 training principles: Progression, Specificity, Overload, Reversibility, Diminishing Returns. Programs that respect all five produce consistent, sustainable results.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">6</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Double-progression protocol: train within a rep range; hit the top end → add 5% load. Simple, effective, applicable to any client at any level.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">7</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Intensity and volume are inversely related. Periodize accordingly. New clients start low intensity — adherence and movement quality first, progressive overload second.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="takeaway-item">
        <div class="ta-num">8</div>
        <div class="ta-text">Reversibility is real: 4 weeks of detraining can erase 2/3 of hard-earned strength gains. Consistent training — even at reduced volume — prevents regression.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

